Essential FTP Server Commands 
These are used in an FTP client to interact with an FTP server: 

    USER <username>: Sends the username to the server.
    PASS <password>: Sends the password.
    LIST / ls: Lists files and directories in the current remote directory.
    PWD: Displays the current working directory on the remote server.
    CWD <dir> / cd: Changes the current remote working directory.
    RETR <filename> / get: Retrieves (downloads) a file from the server.
    STOR <filename> / put: Stores (uploads) a file to the server.
    APPE <filename>: Appends data to an existing file on the server.
    DELE <filename> / delete: Deletes a file.
    MKD <dir> / mkdir: Creates a new directory.
    RMD <dir> / rmdir: Removes a directory.
    TYPE <type>: Sets transfer mode (e.g., TYPE A for ASCII, TYPE I for Binary).
    PASV: Enters passive mode for data transfer.
    QUIT: Disconnects from the server. 

Web Server (HTTP) Commands/Methods 
Web servers use HTTP methods to handle client requests. 

    GET: Requests data from a specified resource.
    POST: Submits data to be processed to a specified resource.
    PUT: Uploads a representation of the requested resource.
    DELETE: Deletes the specified resource.
    HEAD: Same as GET, but returns only the headers, not the body.
    OPTIONS: Describes the communication options for the target resource.
